==English==
{{Wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
First acknowledged in 1912 by the Wentworth American Dialect Dictionary as originating from western Indiana.

===Adjective===
'''irregardless'''

# {{US}} [[regardless|Regardless]], often considered non-standard.

====Usage notes====
Although well attested, this term is often stated to be redundant or incorrect as a double negation, or not a word at all. To avoid controversey, the use of “regardless” is advocated in its place.

====Synonyms====
*(''regardless''): [[irrespective]]

===References===
*This term is marked as an “erroneous or humerous form” in Webster’s New International Dictionary (1909)
*The Shorter OED labels it as ‘chiefly ''N. Amer.'' (''non-standard'' or ''joc.'')’.
*This term does not appear in the Etymological Dictionary of the English Language (1910), Fowler's Modern English Usage (1965){{,}} or Roget’s 21st Century Thesaurus (1992)

